<h3>Motivation and Scope</h3>
<article>
	<div class="firstcolumn">
	<p>
		The operation of a semiconductor device depends on how charge carriers; viz. electrons and holes, respond to applied, built-in and scattering potentials. For much of the past 40 years, as semiconductor devices have transitioned from point-contact transistors to megabit memories, the phenomenological drift-diffusion model – charges drift under applied field and diffuse under a concentration gradient – has served as the backbone of device analysis. 
	</p>
	<p>
		At the very fundamental level electrons & holes in semiconductors are quantum mechanical particles whose wave functions are determined by the crystal potential & applied bias. However, at a macroscopic level the electron and hole behavior can be phenomenologically modeled by considering the average of an enormous number of nearly chaotic trajectories. Consideration of such (thermodynamic)
	</p>
	<fig>
		<%= image_tag 'proposalimg1.png', :href => 'proposalimg1.png' %>
		<p>Fig. 1</p>
	</fig>
	</div>
	<div class="secondcolumn">
	<p>ensembles naturally leads to the definition of system response functions like diffusivity and mobility. The electron/hole behavior can be well modeled by a drift-diffusion equation which is discussed in the next section. </p>
	<p>
		An important application of these drift-diffusion solvers lies in understanding carrier transport in light emitting devices. A light emitting device is a p-n junction diode operated in forward bias. The electrons and holes travel in opposing directions towards the depletion region where a quantum well is strategically placed. The carriers fall into this well and are confined by the potential barriers. This confinement enhances carrier recombination leading to a higher emission efficiency. The potential landscape in which the charge carrier travels thus decides where it will eventually end up. The potential landscape is influence by the local composition. A varying potential landscape generates a field which leads to carrier “drift”. Moreover, since the p-region of the diode has an excess of holes and the n-region of the diode has excess electrons there is a variation in the chemical potential – this concentration gradient leads to diffusion. 
	</p>
	<p>
		A characterization technique called Atom Probe Tomography enables one to obtain details of local composition fluctuations; which in turn influence the potential landscape. Thus the simulation of the final charge density distribution profile from an experimentally obtained composition (elemental distribution) in the Light emitting device is the goal of this investigation. 
	</p>
	</div>
</article>
