<h3>Methodology</h3>
<article>
	<div class="firstcolumn">
	<p>
		Three equations are involved in the Drift-Diffusion Model.
	</p>
	<div class='eqn'> 
	<div lang='latex'>\nabla^2V=\frac{q}{\epsilon}(n_i exp(\frac{E_{fn}-qV}{k_BT}-n_i exp(\frac{-Efp+qV}{k_BT}+N_B)</div>
	<p>Equation. 1</p>
	</div>
	<p>
		This is the Poisson equation which describe the relationship between the charge (right) and the potential(left) derived from coulomb potential. However, this is a non-linear equation of V, therefore needs to be turned into linear form and solved iteratively.  
	</p>
	<div class='eqn'> 
		<div lang='latex'>J_n-R_n-G_n=0=\frac{\partial n}{\partial t}</div>
		<div lang='latex'>J_p-R_p-G_p=0=\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}</div>
		<p>Equation. 2</p>
	</div>
	<p>
		This is the continuity equation where the J stands for current, which arises from the drift part and the diffusion part. And since we are solving the steady state, the charge distribution will be constant with time.
	</p>

	
	</div>
	<div class="secondcolumn">
	<p>
		Total variables in the systems are n, p and V. However, due to Fermi-Dirac distribution, the n and p can be expressed with: 
	</p>
	<div class='eqn'> <div lang='latex'>n=n_i exp( \frac{E_{fn}-qV}{k_BT})</div> <p>Equation. 3</p></div> 
	<p>
		Therefore, there are total three variables Efn, Efp and V. However, due to the convergence issue, three other variables ϕn, ϕp and V should be used. 
	</p>
		<h4>Problem Size</h4>
	<p>
		To estimate the size of the problem, the ∆x is equal to Debye length LD.
	</p>
	<div class='eqn'> 
		<div lang='latex'>L_D=\sqrt{\frac{\epsilon k_B T}{q^2 N}}</div>
		<p>Equation. 4</p>
	</div>
	<p>
		Therefore, it is in the range of 100A. Given a 1D problem with 10000A size of LED chip, there will need to be 1000 points. The 3D problem will scale to 10^9 points. However, if the composition of LED is changing with the dimension of atomic size(3.11A), the 3D problem size increases to 10^12. 
	</p>
	</div>
</article>
